This error usually occurs when the component consuming the context is either outside the Context Provider in the component tree, or the default value of the context is undefined and the provider hasn't initialized yet.

Here is the safest way to consume context by creating a custom hook that throws a helpful error if used outside the provider:

```jsx
import React, { createContext, useContext, useState } from 'react';

const AuthContext = createContext(undefined);

export function AuthProvider({ children }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: 'Admin' });
  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
}

// Custom hook for safe consumption
export function useAuth() {
  const context = useContext(AuthContext);
  if (context === undefined) {
    throw new Error('useAuth must be used within an AuthProvider');
  }
  return context;
}
```

Tell the client to replace their `useContext(AuthContext)` calls with `useAuth()` so it catches the exact rendering issue safely.

To use external images with the Next.js `<Image />` component, you must whitelist the external domain in your `next.config.js` (or `next.config.mjs`) file to prevent abuse of the Next.js image optimization API.

Here is how you fix it:

1. Update your `next.config.js`:
```javascript
/** @type {import('next').Config} */
const nextConfig = {
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      {
        protocol: 'https',
        hostname: 'example-cdn.com', // Replace with your external domain
        port: '',
        pathname: '/**', // Allow all paths under this domain
      },
    ],
  },
};

module.exports = nextConfig;
```

2. Then restart your Next.js development server. The `<Image src="https://example-cdn.com/photo.jpg" width={500} height={500} alt="Photo" />` component will now work perfectly.

Alright, Harry! Building an admin dashboard is a classic, and a great way to solidify your React and Tailwind skills. Let's get this scaffolded for you.

For a responsive sidebar and main content area, we'll set up a basic layout that collapses the sidebar on smaller screens.

Here's a foundational structure using React components and Tailwind CSS classes. I'll break down what each part does.

```jsx
// src/components/AdminLayout.jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

