  };

  return (
    <div className="flex min-h-screen">
      {/* Sidebar */}
      <aside
        className={`bg-gray-800 text-white w-64 space-y-6 py-7 px-2 absolute inset-y-0 left-0 transform ${
          isSidebarOpen ? 'translate-x-0' : '-translate-x-full'
        } md:relative md:translate-x-0 transition duration-200 ease-in-out`}
      >
        <h1 className="text-2xl font-semibold text-center">ClientDash</h1>
        <nav>
          <a
            href="#"
            className="block py-2.5 px-4 rounded transition duration-200 hover:bg-gray-700 hover:text-white"
          >
            Dashboard
          </a>
          <a
            href="#"
            className="block py-2.5 px-4 rounded transition duration-200 hover:bg-gray-700 hover:text-white"
          >
            Users
          </a>
          <a
            href="#"
            className="block py-2.5 px-4 rounded transition duration-200 hover:bg-gray-700 hover:text-white"
          >
            Settings
          </a>
        </nav>
      </aside>

      {/* Main Content Area */}
      <main className="flex-1">
        {/* Header/Navbar */}
        <header className="bg-white shadow p-4">
          <div className="container mx-auto flex justify-between items-center">
            <button onClick={toggleSidebar} className="md:hidden text-gray-600 focus:outline-none">
              {isSidebarOpen ? '✕' : '☰'}
            </button>
            <h2 className="text-2xl font-semibold">Dashboard Overview</h2>
            {/* Add user profile/logout links here */}
          </div>
        </header>

        {/* Content */}
        <div className="p-8">
          {children}
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  );
};

export default AdminLayout;
```

And here’s how you’d use it in your `App.js` (or wherever you want to render the dashboard):

```jsx
// src/App.js
import React from 'react';
import AdminLayout from './components/AdminLayout';
import './index.css'; // Make sure your Tailwind CSS is imported

function App() {
  return (
    <AdminLayout>
      {/* This is where your dashboard content goes */}
      <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">Welcome to the Dashboard!</h1>
      <p>This is the main content area. You can put charts, tables, or other components here.</p>
    </AdminLayout>
  );
}

export default App;
```

**Here’s the breakdown:**

1.  **`AdminLayout.jsx` Component:**
    *   **State Management (`useState`):** We use `useState` to keep track of whether the sidebar is open (`isSidebarOpen`).
    *   **Sidebar (`<aside>`):**
        *   It's styled with `bg-gray-800 text-white` for a dark theme.
        *   `w-64` sets a fixed width on larger screens.
        *   The `absolute inset-y-0 left-0` and `transform ${isSidebarOpen ? 'translate-x-0' : '-translate-x-full'}` classes handle the mobile view. On small screens (`md:` breakpoint and below), it's positioned absolutely and slides off-screen when `isSidebarOpen` is false.
        *   `md:relative md:translate-x-0` makes it a permanent, full-width sidebar on medium screens and larger.
        *   `transition duration-200 ease-in-out` ensures a smooth sliding animation.
        *   Basic navigation links are just `<a>` tags for now.
    *   **Main Content Area (`<main>`):**
        *   `flex-1` makes it take up all the remaining horizontal space.
        *   **Header:** Contains a hamburger menu button (`<button>`) that only shows on mobile (`md:hidden`) and toggles the sidebar. It also has a placeholder for the page title.
        *   **Content:** The `p-8` adds padding. `{children}` renders whatever you put *inside* the `AdminLayout` tags in `App.js`.

2.  **`App.js`:**
    *   Simply wraps your main dashboard content with the `AdminLayout` component.

**How it works responsively:**

*   **Mobile:** The sidebar is hidden by default and slides in/out via the hamburger button. The main content takes the full width.
*   **Tablet/Desktop:** The sidebar is always visible on the left, and the main content is to its right.

